e the motivating examples include intracellular and nuclear receptors rather than only transmembrane receptors.\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+# Research for Issue #32046\n+\n+## PMID:33243852 \"Human NLRP1 is a sensor for double-stranded RNA\"\n+\n+This publication supports NLRP1 as a direct dsRNA sensor involved in inflammasome activation during RNA virus infection.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:33243852 \"Biochemical studies revealed that NLRP1 binds dsRNA through its leucine-rich repeat domain, resulting in its NACHT domain gaining adenosine triphosphatase activity. Altogether, these results establish human NLRP1 as a direct sensor for dsRNA and thus RNA virus infection.\"\n+\n+## PMID:34678144 \"Phase separation drives RNA virus-induced activation of the NLRP6 inflammasome\"\n+\n+This publication supports NLRP6 as an innate immune receptor that interacts with dsRNA and activates inflammasome-related responses.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34678144 \"Here, we show that NLRP6 undergoes liquid-liquid phase separation (LLPS) upon interaction with double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) in vitro and in cells, and an intrinsically disordered poly-lysine sequence (K350-354) of NLRP6 is important for multivalent interactions, phase separation, and inflammasome activation.\"\n+\n+## PMID:23273991 \"Structural basis for dsRNA recognition, filament formation, and antiviral signal activation by MDA5\"\n+\n+This publication supports MDA5/IFIH1 as a viral dsRNA receptor that recognizes dsRNA and activates antiviral signaling.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:23273991 \"MDA5, a viral double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) receptor, shares sequence similarity and signaling pathways with RIG-I yet plays essential functions in antiviral immunity through distinct specificity for viral RNA.\"\n+\n+## PMID:32200799 \"Influenza Virus Z-RNAs Induce ZBP1-Mediated Necroptosis\"\n+\n+This publication supports ZBP1 recognition of Z-RNA, a left-handed RNA conformation generated during influenza virus infection, and subsequent innate immune cell death signaling.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32200799 \"Here, we show that replicating IAV generates Z-RNAs, which activate ZBP1 in the nucleus of infected cells.\"\n+\n+## Reference Validation Notes\n+\n+The PMID pages were checked directly on PubMed. `linkml-reference-validator cache reference` was attempted but NCBI returned HTTP 429 rate-limit errors during caching, so the supporting excerpts above were taken from PubMed page content retrieved directly.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/GO_7770072.obo","relativePath":"terms/GO_7770072.obo","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/GO_7770072.obo\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/GO_7770072.obo\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/GO_7770072.obo\n@@ -0,0 +1,15 @@\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770072\n+name: double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Combining with double-stranded RNA to initiate an innate immune response.\" [PMID:23273991, PMID:33243852, PMID:34678144]\n+synonym: \"double-stranded RNA receptor activity\" BROAD []\n+synonym: \"dsRNA immune receptor activity\" EXACT []\n+synonym: \"dsRNA receptor activity\" BROAD []\n+is_a: GO:0038187 ! pattern recognition receptor activity\n+intersection_of: GO:0038023 ! signaling receptor activity\n+intersection_of: has_primary_input CHEBI:67208 ! double-stranded RNA\n+relationship: has_part GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-10T02:08:02Z\n","additions":15,"dele